## {{ rule.title }}

When you earn wages in euros and file in the United States, the IRS lets you translate the year's gross wages at a single annual average exchange rate rather than spot-converting every paycheck. The rate comes from the IRS yearly average currency exchange rates table.

For 2025 the IRS yearly average is **{{ rule.inputs_by_key["us.fx.eur_per_usd"].value }} EUR per USD**. Your gross wages of **{{ rule.inputs_by_key["us.wages.eur"].value }} EUR** are translated by dividing by that rate, giving **{{ rule.outputs[0].value | money(currency="USD") }}** of U.S. wage income for [Form 1040](https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-1040) line 1a.

This is the same translation method described in the IRS yearly-average rate guidance. The result feeds AGI assembly at stage US25-07.

